Russian Communism is making a comeback
Moscow — A year ago, while on leave from my teaching position at a university in the United States, I returned to my hometown, Moscow.
My destination was not a stronghold of freedom of speech.
But this place still retained some degree of freedom.
Opposition leader Alexei Navalny once traveled across the country to seek support from politicians not controlled by the Kremlin.
Protests by the public erupted.
Independent non-governmental organizations operate domestically.
Journalists and analysts do not necessarily follow the Kremlin's line.
Meanwhile, the Communist Party is widely regarded as a relic of history.
Since then, Navalny has been imprisoned, and the protest movement he initiated has been suppressed.
The anti-corruption foundation was dissolved due to "extremism," while its members are facing exile or investigation.
Almost every day, journalists, media outlets, human rights advocates, or independent organizations are added to the "foreign agent" list — even worse — labeled as "undesirable."
In the past year, Russia has been in a non-free state, though not far away, but very intense.
For example, in 2012, a law was enacted to designate foreign agents, aiming to undermine or discredit institutions or individuals engaged in "political activities" while receiving funding from abroad.
However, the application of this law has become increasingly arbitrary, to the point where retweeting has now become a reason for being labeled as a foreign agent.
（The "unwanted" label will lead to complete elimination.
）This year alone, a record 101 entities were added to the list of foreign agents.
The cumulative total of 359 includes 88 media-related organizations and individuals.
According to the Russian government, the above "agents" must be listed on the list because they "influence national politics."
But the core goal of journalism and propaganda is certainly to influence politics.
This is precisely the issue: although President Vladimir Putin has positioned himself to continue controlling Russian politics for the foreseeable future, he views criticism as a threat to his survival.
Despite all this silence and persecution, the Communist Party, an unlikely group, has survived and become the only real opposition within the Kremlin.
This is largely due to Navalny's "smart voting" strategy — that is, urging people to support the forces most likely to defeat the candidates backed by the Kremlin — and the Communist Party has performed strongly in the recent parliamentary and regional elections.
Official data shows that Communist Party candidates won 18.9% of the votes for the State Duma (parliament), while the Kremlin-backed United Russia party received nearly 49.8%.
However, the Communists refused to accept this result, insisting that the vote was rigged.
In fact, some experts estimate that they should have received about 30% of the votes, while the United Russia party should have received about 35%.
For many Russians, communists seem to be more respected than Putin now.
But they are no longer the original communists.
They not only do not deny earthly pleasures; party members even wear fur coats, are enthusiastic about traveling abroad, drive foreign cars, and use social media.
Some are millionaires — for example, the charismatic agricultural chief Pavel Grudinin (who was banned from participating in last month's elections).
Despite being led by the 77-year-old Gennadiy Zyuganov, the party is increasingly influenced and supported by younger members.
Nikolay Bondarenko is an example.
The 36-year-old Bondarenko, nicknamed "Red Navalniy," severely criticized the poorly designed pension reform of 2018.
Recently, when a regional minister claimed that Russians should be able to "eat better" with a monthly salary of just 3,500 rubles (about $50), Bondarenko recorded on his YouTube channel his efforts to prove the minister wrong.
Despite being threatened with disqualification, Bondarenko was still allowed to participate in the recent State Duma elections.
Although he received support from the Navalny's Smart Voting system, he still lost to the candidate from the United Russia party.
But his potential should not be overlooked: he recently came up with a protest headline accusing "the state and government took over" United Russia.
Then there is 43-year-old Anastasia Yudashova.
Like Bondarenko, she astonishingly lost the last election.
But she is still very — — and increasingly — — popular.
Thanks to the intelligent voting system, another rising star, the elegant Yekaterina Ngalicheva, was elected to the Moscow City Duma in 2019.
Ironically, the modernization of the Communist Party reflects people's yearning for the past: in 1917, Lenin's Bolsheviks promised justice and equality, and the country that achieved these ideals, although strict, was still not devoid of fairness and compassion.
In addition, like the liberal Navalny, today's Communist Party represents a predictable and consistent vision, under which an individual's wild ideas would not affect everyone.
It is precisely based on such logic that all the opponents of the Kremlin are increasingly uniting: forming the "United Russia" party, a unified Russia that can oppose Putin.
This situation is not limited to Russia alone.
In the recent parliamentary elections in the Czech Republic, Andrej Babiš — also known as Czech Donald Trump — failed to be re-elected as prime minister, as the opposition alliance set aside their ideological differences and formed a united coalition, with leader Petr Fiala likely to lead the new government together with another opposition alliance.
As Fiala said, "People have had enough of populists," and they want "normal, competent, and decent politics."
The opposition in Hungary will also present a unified election list for next year's parliamentary elections and send a single candidate to run for prime minister.
Of course, the Czech Republic still maintains a democratic system, so Babiš is preparing to join the opposition forces.
Overthrowing Putin, however, is far more difficult, and it is not hard to predict more measures aimed at dismantling the Communist Party altogether.
But the above approach also brings risks to the Kremlin.
Now the situation is that the president claims that Russian democracy "has not died," and points to the existence of an "active opposition" as evidence, which suggests that he at least still has an interest in pretending that he is not leading Russia toward near-totalitarianism.
Putin says he only wants stability.
Yet his regime is pushing Russia toward a more turbulent situation.
If the Kremlin were to create and implement rules as capriciously as it has treated Russian liberals, driving the Communist Party underground, social explosion would be more likely to occur.
But if it decides to stop suppressing, the Russian communists — yes, the communists — could become an underestimated force.
